Author-Name:    Walker, Donald A
Title:   Walras's Theories of Tatonnement. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 758-74
Issue: 4
Volume: 95
Year: 1987
Month:  August 
Abstract:
  It is shown that Leon Walras developed two separate theories of
 tatonnement. One is a disequilibrium-production model. The other is a
 pledges model, in which transactions and production occur only at the
 equilibrium set of prices. These models are explained, and the manner in
 which they appear in the vari ous editions of Walras's Elements is used to
 account for the developm ent of conflicting interpretations of his
 writings on tatonnement. It is shown that the disequilibrium-production
 model is more representa tive of Walras's work than the pledges model and
 that the latter is i ncompatible with the theories of particular aspects
 of economic behav ior on which the Elements depends for its verisimilitude
 and explanat ory power.  Copyright 1987 by University of Chicago Press.
